{"parse":{"title":"Disability Rights Education and Defense Fund","pageid":44006608,"revid":851810467,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><caption class=\"fn org\">Disability Rights Education and Defense Fund</caption><tbody><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Logo_for_the_Disability_Rights_Education_and_Defense_Fund.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Logo for the Disability Rights Education and Defense Fund.png\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/8/80/Logo_for_the_Disability_Rights_Education_and_Defense_Fund.png\" width=\"220\" height=\"111\" data-file-width=\"220\" data-file-height=\"111\" /></a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.6em;\">Abbreviation</th><td class=\"nickname\">\nDREDF</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.6em;\">Formation</th><td class=\"note\">\n1979</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.6em;\">Website</th><td>\n<span class=\"url\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://dredf.org\">dredf<wbr />.org</a></span></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><b>The Disability Rights Education and Defense Fund (DREDF)</b>, located in <a href=\"/wiki/Berkeley,_California\" title=\"Berkeley, California\">Berkeley, California</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Washington,_DC\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Washington, DC\">Washington, DC</a>, USA is a national cross-disability <a href=\"/wiki/Civil_rights\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Civil rights\">civil rights</a> law and policy center directed by individuals with disabilities and parents who have children with disabilities. Founded in 1979, DREDF advances the civil and human rights of people with disabilities through legal advocacy, training, education, and public policy and legislative development.The Berkeley office is located in the <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ed_Roberts_Campus&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Ed Roberts Campus (page does not exist)\">Ed Roberts Campus</a>.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#The_1980s\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">The 1980s</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#The_1990s\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1.2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">The 1990s</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#The_2000s_and_Beyond\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1.3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">The 2000s and Beyond</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Disability_Rights_Education_and_Defense_Fund&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>An outgrowth of the <a href=\"/wiki/Independent_Living\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Independent Living\">Independent Living</a> Movement, which had deep roots in Berkeley, California, DREDF was the first national, cross-disability civil rights organization in the United States to be founded, managed, and directed by an alliance of people with disabilities and parents of children with disabilities.<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citation needed\"><span title=\"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (February 2015)\">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> The organization derived its name from other historical civil rights groups such as the <a href=\"/wiki/Women%E2%80%99s_Legal_Defense_Fund\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Women\u2019s Legal Defense Fund\">Women\u2019s Legal Defense Fund</a>, the <a href=\"/wiki/NAACP_Legal_Defense_and_Educational_Fund\" title=\"NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund\">NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund</a> (LDF), and the <a href=\"/wiki/Mexican_American_Legal_Defense_and_Educational_Fund\" title=\"Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund\">Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund</a> (MALDEF).\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"The_1980s\">The 1980s</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Disability_Rights_Education_and_Defense_Fund&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: The 1980s\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>DREDF challenges discrimination, prejudice and social exclusion of people with disabilities. Its early efforts focused on:\n</p>\n<ul><li>building alliances with the national civil rights leadership</li>\n<li>preventing the <a href=\"/wiki/Reagan_administration\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Reagan administration\">Reagan administration</a>'s Task Force on Regulatory Relief's<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> attempts to de-regulate the <a href=\"/wiki/Section_504_of_the_Rehabilitation_Act\" title=\"Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act\">Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act</a> of 1973</li>\n<li>protecting regulations implementing the Education for All Handicapped Children Act (later renamed the <a href=\"/wiki/Individuals_with_Disabilities_Education_Act\" title=\"Individuals with Disabilities Education Act\">Individuals with Disabilities Education Act</a> (IDEA)), the federal law establishing the right to a free, appropriate, public education for all children with disabilities</li>\n<li>working for federal civil rights legislation affecting people with disabilities such as the <a href=\"/wiki/Civil_Rights_Restoration_Act_of_1987\" title=\"Civil Rights Restoration Act of 1987\">Civil Rights Restoration Act of 1987</a>, the <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.civilrights.org/monitor/august1986/art5p1.html\">1986 Handicapped Children's Protection Act</a>, the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act Amendments, and the Fair Housing Act Amendments</li>\n<li>writing, co-authoring, and coordinating <a href=\"/wiki/Amicus_curiae\" title=\"Amicus curiae\">amicus curiae</a> briefs on early <a href=\"/wiki/Disability_rights\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Disability rights\">disability rights</a> matters heard by the <a href=\"/wiki/U.S._Supreme_Court\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"U.S. Supreme Court\">U.S. Supreme Court</a> including <i>Smith v. Robinson, Darrone, and Arline</i></li>\n<li>building a national civil rights <a href=\"/wiki/Advocacy\" title=\"Advocacy\">advocacy</a> network of <a href=\"/wiki/People_with_disabilities\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"People with disabilities\">people with disabilities</a> and parents by providing in-depth training on the then-new civil rights laws, Section 504 and IDEA</li></ul>\n<p>After a decade-long record of advocacy training, and legislative, legal, and policy victories, DREDF was uniquely situated to play a significant role in the enactment of the landmark civil rights law, the <a href=\"/wiki/Americans_with_Disabilities_Act_of_1990\" title=\"Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990\">Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990</a> (ADA). DREDF's governmental affairs director, <a href=\"/wiki/Patrisha_Wright\" title=\"Patrisha Wright\">Patrisha Wright</a>, known as \"The General,\" led the national coalition advocating for enactment of the proposed law, and <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Arlene_Mayerson&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Arlene Mayerson (page does not exist)\">Arlene Mayerson</a>, DREDF's legal director, developed briefing materials, legal memoranda, and legal opinions about the impact of proposed legislation at the request of members of Congress. Policy analyst, <a href=\"/wiki/Marilyn_Golden\" title=\"Marilyn Golden\">Marilyn Golden</a> led community organizing efforts. Senator <a href=\"/wiki/Tom_Harkin\" title=\"Tom Harkin\">Tom Harkin</a>, was lead sponsor of the ADA.\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"The_1990s\">The 1990s</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Disability_Rights_Education_and_Defense_Fund&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: The 1990s\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Following passage of the ADA, DREDF focused on preserving the new law and shaping its implementation by providing nationwide training and technical assistance<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> and by writing and publishing a legal series that presented ADA legislative history and commentary.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> In a series of cases, DREDF wins the right of children with disabilities requiring healthcare assistance (such as diabetes and asthma) to receive such assistance in pre-school and recreational settings. In an effort to promote community integration, DREDF works with community and legal groups to challenge the continued institutionalization of disabled residents in San Francisco's Laguna Honda Hospital and to create community-based alternatives. Other ADA litigation also opens doors to movie theaters, hotels, banking services, and gas stations. DREDF represents Members of Congress is a trilogy of cases involving the definition of disability under the ADA. Continuing its commitment to IDEA implementation, DREDF achieves a series of litigation victories that establish a national precedent for full inclusion of children with disabilities in regular classes in <i>Holland v. Sacramento City School District</i><sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> and establishes educational rights for children with disabilities in East Palo Alto, California. As interest in disability rights gains international momentum, disability rights leaders from 17 countries invite legal and policy staff to consult and collaborate on strategies for advancing policy in their countries.\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"The_2000s_and_Beyond\">The 2000s and Beyond</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Disability_Rights_Education_and_Defense_Fund&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: The 2000s and Beyond\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>DREDF organizes \"From Principles to Practice,\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> the first international disability right law symposium to be held in the United States, bringing together 150 attorneys and legal advocates from 57 countries. Transnational Publishers releases <i>Disability Rights Law and Policy: International and National Perspectives</i>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> edited by <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Silvia_Yee&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Silvia Yee (page does not exist)\">Silvia Yee</a>, Esq. and <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mary_Lou_Breslin&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Mary Lou Breslin (page does not exist)\">Mary Lou Breslin</a>. As traditional barriers to equal participation for people with disabilities begin to bend to the effect of the ADA, DREDF identifies and focuses attention on emerging challenges including thwarting legislative attempts to legalize assisted suicide and increasing access to healthcare services and improving healthcare outcomes. DREDF conducts healthcare research and publishes outcomes in peer-reviewed journals. As the US House and Senate consider enactment of the Affordable Care Act (ACA), DREDF advocates for enhanced protections and rights for people with disabilities. Following enactment of the ACA, DREDF advocates for ADA implementation in healthcare programs and services, drafts comments with colleagues on proposed regulations that create accessible medical equipment standards, and collaborates with senior groups as the ACA tests models that combine clinical care and long-term services and supports for low-income people with disabilities and seniors.\nLitigation against <a href=\"/wiki/Netflix#Closed_captioning\" title=\"Netflix\">Netflix</a> results in a landmark settlement that requires captioning for all streaming media the company offers, thus marking progress on applying the ADA to Internet-only businesses.<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> Other litigation<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> succeeds in requiring the US Social Security Administration to provide all notices to beneficiaries in alternative formats.<sup id=\"cite_ref-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Disability_Rights_Education_and_Defense_Fund&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Burke, Thomas F. (2002). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://publishing.cdlib.org/ucpressebooks/view?docId=kt9n39q5pr;brand=ucpress\"><i>Lawyers, Lawsuits, and Legal Rights</i></a>. Berkeley Los Angeles London: University of California Press. pp.&#160;72 \u2013 72.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Lawyers%2C+Lawsuits%2C+and+Legal+Rights&amp;rft.place=Berkeley+Los+Angeles+London&amp;rft.pages=72+-+72&amp;rft.pub=University+of+California+Press&amp;rft.date=2002&amp;rft.aulast=Burke&amp;rft.aufirst=Thomas+F.&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fpublishing.cdlib.org%2Fucpressebooks%2Fview%3FdocId%3Dkt9n39q5pr%3Bbrand%3Ducpress&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADisability+Rights+Education+and+Defense+Fund\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Babcock, Charles R. (March 2, 1982). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/access/137262962.html?FMT=ABS&amp;FMTS=ABS:AI&amp;type=historic&amp;date=Mar+4%2C+1982&amp;author=By+Charles+R.+Babcock+Washington+Post+Staff+Writer&amp;pub=The+Washington+Post+(1974-Current+file)&amp;edition=&amp;startpage=A27&amp;desc=Handicapped+Policy+Undergoing+a+Rewrite\">\"Handicapped Policy Undergoing a Rewrite\"</a>. <i>Washington Post</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">January 14,</span> 2013</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Washington+Post&amp;rft.atitle=Handicapped+Policy+Undergoing+a+Rewrite&amp;rft.date=1982-03-02&amp;rft.aulast=Babcock&amp;rft.aufirst=Charles+R.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fpqasb.pqarchiver.com%2Fwashingtonpost_historical%2Faccess%2F137262962.html%3FFMT%3DABS%26FMTS%3DABS%3AAI%26type%3Dhistoric%26date%3DMar%2B4%252C%2B1982%26author%3DBy%2BCharles%2BR.%2BBabcock%2BWashington%2BPost%2BStaff%2BWriter%26pub%3DThe%2BWashington%2BPost%2B%281974-Current%2Bfile%29%26edition%3D%26startpage%3DA27%26desc%3DHandicapped%2BPolicy%2BUndergoing%2Ba%2BRewrite&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADisability+Rights+Education+and+Defense+Fund\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Americans-Disabilities-Act-implementation-guide/dp/B0006QG0AC/ref=sr_1_2?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1422822139&amp;sr=1-2&amp;keywords=The+Americans+with+Disabilities+Act%3A+A+Guide+to+Implementation\">\"The ADA, An Implementation Guide\"</a>. <i>Amazon</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">1 February</span> 2015</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Amazon&amp;rft.atitle=The+ADA%2C+An+Implementation+Guide&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FAmericans-Disabilities-Act-implementation-guide%2Fdp%2FB0006QG0AC%2Fref%3Dsr_1_2%3Fs%3Dbooks%26ie%3DUTF8%26qid%3D1422822139%26sr%3D1-2%26keywords%3DThe%2BAmericans%2Bwith%2BDisabilities%2BAct%253A%2BA%2BGuide%2Bto%2BImplementation&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADisability+Rights+Education+and+Defense+Fund\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Arlene, Mayerson. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://dredf.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/DisRightsLaw-RootsPresentChallenges_10_07.pdf\">\"Disability Rights Law: Roots, Present Challenges, and Future Collaboration\"</a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>. <i>dredf.org</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">1 February</span> 2015</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=dredf.org&amp;rft.atitle=Disability+Rights+Law%3A+Roots%2C+Present+Challenges%2C+and+Future+Collaboration&amp;rft.aulast=Arlene&amp;rft.aufirst=Mayerson&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fdredf.org%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2012%2F10%2FDisRightsLaw-RootsPresentChallenges_10_07.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADisability+Rights+Education+and+Defense+Fund\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Arlene, Mayerson (1994). <i>Americans With Disabilities Act Annotated: Legislativ